replies.comment info:
@Giulia AOSE 

I appreciate your thoughtful comments on how these graphs affect your community. 

I wonder how inter-connected each of these graphs are and what the US can do to help US grow in rank in some of the categories directly affecting people's happiness.

@Emma M 
I also wondered how our education rank managed to stay the same with all the upheavals during school. 
Do you think life satisfaction will increase the further we move away from COVID and people start going back to work?

@Dorin 

Trust in the federal government has been trending down for many years. The slope graphs really make it easy to identify the downward slide, and I wonder how fast it fell since COVID.
Do you think government mistrust affects any of the other categories, like life satisfaction? What makes you and your classmates happy?

@Ermal 
Take a look at the y axis on the life expectancy graph: it appears that the #1 ranked country also dropped though not as much as the US. 
I wonder which countries also dropped like the US did, and I wonder which country shot up to #1 (that country was below the US). What do you think contributed to that jump?

@Nicole Nektalov 
The slope graph makes it easier for readers to follow the overall trends in the data, and it is startling to see the drop in some of the categories.
It would have been nice for the graph to be interactive so we could see which countries are closest or furthest apart in these categories.

@Jeremy Nassimiha 

I also wish we could have seen which countries were just above and below the USA.

The USA GDP may still be high, but there are more concerning factors in these graphs. Which graph surprised you the most?

@Juliana AOSE 

Great correlation with those three graphs. I wonder how closely related they are and if the changes with any of the other graph had an affect on life satisfaction/expectancy and social isolation.

Can an increase in government trust change those graph results and rankings for the better?
